): variant of   Squire  , from a northern form of the word."]},{"name":"Quire","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Squire  .","Scottish or Irish: shortened form of   McQuire   (see   McGuire  )."]},{"name":"Squires","meanings":["English: variant of   Squire  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Scuderi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmelo, Salvatore, Angelo, Carlo, Gaetano, Vito, Antonio, Dante, Mario, Rocco, Rosario, Antonino, Biaggio, Eduardo, Ermelinda, Margarita.","Italian (Sicily): status name equivalent to   Squire  , from <i>scudiero</i>, <i>scutiero</i>, dialect <i>scuteri</i> ‘shieldbearer’ (from medieval Latin <i>scutarius</i>, an agent derivative of <i>scutum</i> ‘shield’). In Byzantium, the Greek word <i>skoutarios</i> denoted a member of the imperial guard."]},{"name":"Square","meanings":["English (Devon) and Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Squire  ."]},{"name":"Squier","meanings":["English: variant of   Squire  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Squire was born in 1380, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Unknown (Squire). He died in 1456, in his hometown, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1380–1456":"1380–1456","–Female":"Surnud","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1380":"1380","1490":"1490","St Cleer, Cornwall, England":"St Cleer, Cornwall, England","Squires, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":